title: Polarization measurements and optical model analyses of neutron scattering at 3.2 MeV

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.222, Issue.1, p.93 (1974)

x4freetext: Polarization measurements and optical model analyses
of neutron scattering at 3.2 MeV
Furnished a 650 keV deuteron beam with a
mean current of 500 micro-A
- half of the neutron spectrum width
.The neutron producing targets were 1 mg/cm2 titanium
deuterium targets with copper backing placed at 45
degrees to the deuteron beam.
.Mean neutron energy was 3.2 MeV and total width of
neutron spectrum about 300 keV.
.Neutrons were collimated to a narrow beam the width
of which was the same as the scatterer diameter.
.Natural targets of Ti,Cr,Fe,Ni,Cu,Zn,Sr,Zr,Nb,Mo,Ag,
Cd,Sn,Sb,Te,Ba,W,Tl,Pb,Bi.
.Their lengths and diam varied between respectively
24 and 40 mm and 30 and 50 mm but were always smaller
than the mean free path for 3.2 MeV neutrons.
Measurements made by transmission and restricted
to forward angle between 30 and 75 degrees.
Four neutron NE-213 scintillator
detectors, 5 cm in diam,7.5 cm in length could be
positioned at angles between 30 and 150 degrees in a
large paraffin shielding block.
* The protons were detected with a silicon surface
barrier detector
.Polarizations are calculated from the asymmetries
with p1= -15%,by the following formula.
P(cor)= A*F*P(exp)- B -C + (P1-sqrt(P1))
where- P(cor) is the corrected datum
- P(exp) is the raw datum
- F the correction factor for inelastic scat.
- A,B,C terms which depend of the folded
Legendre polynomials.
Comparison with other data and optical model
analyses.
.For multiple scattering,for geometrical spread,and
for inelastic scattering.
Statistical error given.
